British legislators have rejected beleaguered Prime Minister Theresa May’s Brexit deal, plunging the future of the UK’s bid to leave the EU deeper into crisis and raising the possibility of a delayed departure. MPs in the lower chamber House of Commons on Tuesday voted 391 to 242 against May’s plan, fewer than 24 hours after she claimed to have won meaningful concessions from Brussels over the deal’s contentious so-called “backstop” clause. 